            <biogHist>
                <p>Magnus Nicolson [Manus MacNeacail] was born, the son of John Nicolson, postman,
                    and Ann Nicolson n√©e Gillies. The census of 1861 has him listed as a postboy
                    aged 16. By the time of his marriage to Christina McLean in 1869, Magnus was
                    living in Glasgow, working as a postman like his father before him. In the 1881
                    census the couple are listed as having four children: John (10), Charles (6),
                    Magnus (2) and Christina (two months). By the 1891 census, Charles is also
                    listed as a postman and his older brother John as a clerk. Ten years later,
                    Magnus Nicolson is still working as a postman with son Charles now listed as a
                    Hackney Carriage driver. Magnus Nicolson died in Millport in the parish of
                    Cumbrae in the County of Bute in 1909; his death certificate was signed by his
                    cousin John Angus MacRae. </p>
                <p>Alexander Carmichael visited Nicolson in Carbost in February 1861, collecting a
                    story.</p>
